<promed@promedmail.org>

[While COVID is basically a public health problem, it also is a work-life issue affecting how and where we conduct daily business, and it also affects our old concepts of live entertainment and travel and sociability. In the future, in the developed world, there will likely continue to be focal outbreaks, as there are with measles, in pockets where vaccination is low or where new strains emerge that are poorly neutralized by vaccine, as with flu. Long-term sequelae are a serious problem not only for those experiencing them, but also for society in general, and as a burden on hospitals and health care workers. These may continue for years.

With time, people will come to accept the level of risk COVID raises. Wearing of masks will always be a good preventative measure for those at greater risk and may be worn more commonly in the USA and elsewhere, as they were in China before COVID. As Sylvie Briand, head of infectious-hazards management at the World Health Organization in Geneva, Switzerland stated above, "cultural, ethical and political factors will differ widely between regions", affecting the point at which the government will launch an all-out response. And individuals will need to make personal decisions as to what level of risk they will tolerate.

In low- and middle-income countries, the problem is more severe. See Hotez PJ, Fenwick A, Molyneux D. The new COVID-19 poor and the neglected tropical diseases resurgence. Infect Dis Poverty. 2021; 10: 10. https://doi.org/10.1186/s40249-020-00784-2.

Furthermore, practices that lead to emergence of zoonotic pathogens and spillover into new naive hosts need to be curtailed, as they have global consequences. It is important to find sources of food that sustain people that are not sylvatic wild animals or domestically farmed and sold wild animals. - Mod.LK]

