[4] COVID-19 recurrence
Date: Wed 5 May 2021
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/05/news-scan-may-05-2021


Less than 0.1% of all COVID-positive patients in the Intermountain Healthcare system had probable or possible recurrence of SARS-CoV-2 infection, according to a PLoS One study yesterday [4 May 2021; Peltan ID, Beesley SJ, Webb BJ, et al. Evaluation of potential COVID-19 recurrence in patients with late repeat positive SARS-CoV-2 testing. PLoS ONE 2021; 16(5): e0251214. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0251214]

The full cohort of 23 176 COVID-19 patients was pared down to 1301 patients who had at least one additional SARS-CoV-2 test 60 or more days after the initial diagnosis. Almost 10% (122) had a positive test, of which 114 had sufficient data for recurrence evaluation (median test interval, 85.5 days).

Using both clinical and cycle threshold (Ct) values, the researchers found that 4 patients had probable and 6 had possible COVID-19 recurrence. Taken together, that's 4.3 people with probable or possible COVID recurrence per 10 000 patients (95% confidence interval [CI], 2.1 to 7.9), or 0.04%. Of the 4 patients with probable recurrent infections, all had symptoms and 3 required a higher level of medical care than with the initial illness.

The researchers note that using the adjudication standard adapted from Abu Raddard and colleagues (published in Clinical Infectious Diseases, 2020 https://doi.org/10.1093/cid/ciaa1846) resulted in a probable or possible COVID-19 recurrence in 31.9 per 10 000 patients (CI, 25.1 to 40.1). Probable and possible recurrence numbers also increased to 44 COVID-19 patients if patients were assessed via purely clinical means.

"Neither clinical criteria nor Ct assessment alone appeared sufficient to accurately categorize likelihood of COVID-19 recurrence," the researchers write. "Although reinfection seems more likely in these immunocompetent patients, reactivation is also possible."

